&introduction;
Jalopy core
This part of the manual covers the core Jalopy engine: generic installation and usage instructions along with a detailed discussion of the available switches to customize formatting output.
Installation
System requirements System requrirements
Jalopy requires a properly configured JDK or JRE version 1.3 or later on your system.
Jalopy depends on several freely available Java libraries. For more information regarding this 3rd party libraries refer to .
Dependencies
Incompatibility with Sun JDK 1.4.0
The contained Javadoc parser may not work properly under Sun JDK 1.4.0. Refer to for more information regarding this issue.
Installing Jalopy Installation
Installation depends on the distribution you received. Please refer to the individual Plug-in chapters in for detailed information.
Building from the sources
Prerequisites
The following software must be installed separately, in order to build from the sources:
Jakarta Ant. Jalopy comes with a simple, Ant-based build system. So you first need to obtain and install Ant as outlined in the Ant manual. The build system is only tested against the Ant 1.5 release, but later nightly builds of Ant may also work.
Oasis DocBook XML DTD. You can get it from the OASIS website.
Norman Walsh's DocBook XSL Stylesheets. Download the latest release from SourceForge (http://docbook.sf.net). You have to copy the file extensions/saxon65.jar that comes with the distribution into the /lib folder of your Ant installation directory as this file is needed for sophisticated table generation.
An XSLT processor. The only one I found working with the DocBook XSL release I'm using is Michael Kay's Saxon. You should download the current stable production release from SourceForge (http://saxon.sf.net) and extract the file saxon.jar into the /lib folder of your Ant installation directory.
Building
The basic steps to build Jalopy from the sources are:
Get and install the needed software as outlined in . Make sure Ant is set up correctly.
Get the sources. Currently you don't have a choice but to download the Jalopy source distribution which contains the complete Jalopy sources. Unpack the sources into a directory of your choice.
Change to the directory where the Jalopy sources reside. You should find a directory layout somewhat similar to the following:
<DIR> ant <DIR> build <DIR> docu <DIR> eclipse <DIR> jbuilder <DIR> jdeveloper <DIR> jedit <DIR> main <DIR> netbeans
main contains the core Jalopy runtime sources, docu all documentation, build contains the build system and files related to installation and maintainance, the other (optional) directories contain the sources of the different Plug-ins.
Change directory into /build where the master build script lurks.
Adjust the global build properties to match your installation. The build system uses quite a few properties to control the behaviour and specify additional needed resources. You will find these properties in the file build.properties.
Common properties that have to changed include:
Common build properties
DIR.DOCBOOK.XSL
Specifies the installation directory of the DocBook XSL stylesheets package. Note that you have to specify a protocol, e.g. file:///G:/Programme/docbook-xsl-1.54.0.
DIR.DOCBOOK.DTD
Specifies the path where to find the DocBook XSL DTD.
LIB.PATH.<modulename>
Specifies additional library path(s) needed to build a certain module. Adjust the default path(s) to match your installation.
PACKAGE.PATH.<libraryname>
Specifies the location to a directory containing the package-list file for a given library. This is optional and only needed by Javadoc to resolve links to documentation for external referenced classes. Change the default path(s) to match your installation.
Once everything is set up, you can start a build by using ant target where target describes one of the main build targets (those with a description, use ant -projecthelp to display the available targets). Just typing ant will build the Jalopy core runtime distribution.
When a build is done, you can find the created distribution(s) in the tmp~/dist folder. The build system creates and stores all intermediate files and subdirectories under the tmp~ directory.
If you make changes to the source code, just run Ant again; this will perform a faster incremental rebuild of the target.
Usage
Usage depends on the distribution you received. Please refer to the individual Plug-in chapters in for details.
Preferences
Preferences
Jalopy stores all preferences settings as files inside its settings directory (or subdirectories thereof). This directory is located in the user home directory ($HOME/.jalopy).
Settings directory
A graphical user interface is provided to easily configure the preferences. Please refer to the individual Plug-in chapters in for information on how to display it from within the Plug-in you received.
